author: f3c6123b-d3fa-405c-8e2a-4cedb39bcaa0
description: It\'s not just the commuting time that is regained as a result of remote work. It is the mental energy that goes into commuting. It takes mental energy to drive to work, take public transportation to work, etc. That mental energy is freed up when working from home. That mental drain of commuting is avoided. Employers are the ones to gain as well as the employee when workers have more mental energy available. Also, the vaccines for COVID are not promising more than 3-6 months of immunity due to the mutative nature of COVID. Doctors/scientists are hoping for 1-2 years of immunity. That is a hope, not a promise. The world is still experimenting when it comes to COVID. So COVID is going to be around for a while even with the vaccines. They are not eliminating it as in the case of polio to a large degree. They are only going to be able to control the swiftness of the spread.

description: 18 months ago, I graduated from University. I wanted to be a digital nomad however I couldn\'t risk it and I found comfort in working for companies abroad for 2-3 months and move to another country. Once the pandemic started, I became jobless and I had two choices, either continue the journey in South East Asia as a full time digital nomad or come back to my home country Morocco. I decided to be a full time digital nomad in KL - Malaysia. Times were hard, especially during the 3 months of total lockdown. However, this was the best decision I took. The freedom I feel everyday is worth it. This year was the best year of my life. A year full of downs but most importantly full of lessons. Enjoy the digital nomadic lifestyle.

Once the pandemic started, I became jobless and I had two choices, either continue the journey in South East Asia as a full time digital nomad or come back to my home country Morocco. I decided to be a full time digital nomad in KL - Malaysia. Times were hard, especially during the 3 months of total lockdown. However, this was the best decision I took. The freedom I feel everyday is worth it. This year was the best year of my life. A year full of downs but most importantly full of lessons. Enjoy the digital nomadic lifestyle.

Neil Strauss\' Emergency was a great book for that inspired me to start doing that years ago. As for Medical care, I trust the pulmonary medical care much more in Thailand than I would in the US, especially with the US being overworked and understaffed. description: I think you are massively inflating the maximum potential size of the independent digital sector and at the same time being extremely naive about the site-specific aspects of the world economy. Sectors such as oil and gas, logistics (which is the backbone of e-commerce), manufacturing, construction etc etc are all completely location dependent. And that\'s without mentioning the worlds largest industry; food. Every aspect, from food production and agriculture through to restaurants and delivery services, are not just location dependent but location limited. By this I mean growing different crops is limited to certain climates, soils, humidities etc etc and cooking certain foods is limited to specific audiences in specific locations (Try serving duck-faces in a restaurant in London v a restaurant in Chiang-Mai and you\'ll see what I mean, these things are location specific). I would say maybe 1% (probably an over estimation) of the worlds economic activity is generated via completely location independent means so the digital sector is probably already at saturation point. I also think that lockdown has shocked a lot of people in the community into realising the fragility of a lifestyle without a base. When lockdown hit, a lot of travellers/digital nomads found themselves stranded and needing to be repatriated back to their parents/siblings houses. They have essentually become dependents due to living a lifestyle that purports to be the most independent. I would not be surprised if the DN community shrank considerably because of this pandemic.
